<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobutu Agrees in Principle to Meet Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zairian President Mobutu Sese
Seko has agreed to meet rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila, as has
been suggested by South African President Nelson Mandela, the
presidential special advisor Honore Ngbanda Nzambo announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Ngbanda, who is a member of the negotiation committee appointed
by Mobutu to talk with the rebels, today handed over a letter from
South African President Nelson Mandela to Mobutu inviting the
latter to meet Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Officials in South Africa said that Mobutu and Kabila could
most probably meet next week in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ngbanda said that the date and venue of the talks are "part of
the technical problems that are in the process of being solved,"
and that "the details and methods of this meeting are being
studied and will be announced at a proper time."
</P>
<P>
He said that at the request of President Mandela, both sides of
the negotiation have "the reserving right of not compromising the
very serious things."
</P>
<P>
He also said that the meeting could take place "in less than a
week."
</P>
<P>
On the rebels' call for Mobutu's resignation from his office,
Ngbanda said that it is the Zairian people who should decide who
will be their leaders them through "transparent, just and
non-exclusive elections."
</P>
<P>
"President Mobutu is ready to confront no matter who (in the
elections)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The "finance minister" of the rebels, Mawapanga mwana Nanga,
said on Thursday that Kabila is ready to meet Mobutu "whatever
time for a peaceful transfer of power." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
