<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Local Phone Giant's Earnings Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bell Atlantic Corporation,
which offers local phone service in six mid-Atlantic states and
the District of Columbia, announced Thursday that its earnings
rose sharply in the first quarter of this year, which is said to
have demonstrated the local phone business in the United States
remains remarkably healthy.
</P>
<P>
The company' earnings in the period increased 11 percent from
the comparable period last year to 515.6 million U.S. dollars. And
its number of line grew 3.9 percent from a year earlier to 20.8
million, according to a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
Much of that growth came from second lines, which customers are
using for fax machines and home computers. In the first quarter
Bell Atlantic installed 245,000 second lines, a 20 percent
increase over the comparable period in 1996. It plans to sell one
million additional lines this year.
</P>
<P>
The marked results were scored despite all the regulatory
uncertainty that hangs over it. The company had announced that it
would acquire Nynex, a phone company in New York, in what is
described as a deal trying to become the No. Two company in the
United States only next to At&AMP;T company. But the 22 billion U.S.
dollar merger has been reportedly blocked by the Department of
Justice, which has been conducting an antitrust investigation. the
length and intensity of the investigation has stoked fears that
the Federal Government might kill the deal on the ground that it
will diminish future competition in Bell Atlantic and Nynrx's
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
