<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Falls to 2.7 pct in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain's underlying inflation
rate fell from 2.9 percent to 2.7 percent in March, the lowest
level for two years, but just short of meeting the government's
target rate of 2.5 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Office for National
Statistics (ONS), the headline inflation rate, which includes
mortgage interest payments, also dropped, hitting an annual rate
of 2.6 percent, down from February's 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures were a touch lower than economists had expected and
therefore reduced the pressure for a post-election interest rate
hike, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The ONS noted that a sharp fall in the price of seasonal food
over the month was chiefly responsible for the drop in the
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Seasonal foods have now fallen in price by 15.6 percent over
the past year, the largest decline since 1983. Overall food prices
have fallen 1.6 percent in the last year, the largest fall since
1960, as food retailers have competed on price.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sterling's rise had also contributed to the fall
in food prices, the ONS added.
</P>
<P>
However, inflation rates in households goods, clothing and
footware rose sharply as retailers took advantage of growing
consumer demand to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor Kenneth Clarke said that the figures showed that
Britain's economy is booming while inflation stays well under
control.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition Labor Party seized on the government's
failure to meet the 2.5 percent target as another broken promise
on the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
