<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Extends Ban on Former World Cup Referee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- World soccer governing body FIFA
Friday extended a European ban on a former World Cup referee
accused of bribery, saying further investigations into
match-fixing allegations will be conducted.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said in Zurich that Swiss referee Kurt Roethlisberger
would be "permanently banned from all official activity within
FIFA or any of its member associations."
</P>
<P>
It said it would look into allegations of bribery at a World
Cup qualifier between Switzerland and Norway last November.
</P>
<P>
UEFA banned Roethlisberger for life earlier this month in
connection with an incident before a Champions Cup match between
the Swiss side Grasshoppers and Auxerre of France last fall.
</P>
<P>
UEFA said the Swiss referee had approached Grasshopper
officials and suggested that he might be able to convince Vadim
Zhuk of Belarus, the referee assigned to the match, to favor the
Swiss club for 100,000 Swiss francs (70,000 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
