<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Japanese Motor Giants to Increase Sharing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ford Motor Company of the
United States and the Mazda Motor Corporation of Japan gave agreed
on a plan for a substantial amount of sharing of basic designs,
engines and transmissions in an effort to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in Tokyo, Japan, by Mazda's president, Henry
D.G. Wallace, who a year ago became the first foreigner to be
named president of a major japanese company, the New York Times
reported today quoting a dispatch from Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The new cooperation was depicted by Wallace "enhanced strategic
relationship" between the two companies which began cooperation a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
The new models developed by the two companies are expected to
begin rolling off the assembly lines over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Now, "We try to use the best of both companies and We try not
to duplicate," the newspaper quoted Ford's vice chairman, W. Wayne
Booker, as saying in Detroit, the motor city of the united
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
