<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Military Denies Link with Chemical Exports to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany's defense ministry today
rejected charges by Iran that the government and army knew that
German firms were involved in chemical exports to Iraq,
describing the accusation as "sheer nonsense."
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said the German army had never been
involved in chemical deliveries.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi, chief of the
Iranian Judiciary, said during a prayer ceremony today in Tehran
that Iran had evidence linking the German government and army to
chemical exports to Iraq by German firms during the 1980-1988
Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence, even video tapes, that German firms ... made
chemical exports to Iraq with the awareness and permission of the
German government and army," Yazdi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the chemicals were sent directly to the Iraqi
army and Iran had video tapes showing German officials negotiating
with Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi said Iran would sue 24 German firms and the German
officials that Iran accuses of having helped Iraq produce chemical
weapons. Iran alleges these were used in gas attacks on Iranian
soldiers and civilians during the eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 complaints have reached the Iranian judiciary from
relatives of the toxic gas victims, demanding compensation and
trial of the relevant German firms and government officials.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary chief also called on the 400 war veterans to end
their three-day sit-down demonstration in front of the German
embassy in Tehran, promising to bring their case to international
tribunals.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi also criticized the April 10 Berlin court verdict which
linked Iran's government and religious leadership to the 1992
killings of four Kurdish dissidents in Berlin, calling it
"satanic" and "politically oriented."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian Army Accuses Hutu Rebels of Killing Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Burundian army today said that they
had discovered some 100 corpses of civilians who were killed by
the Hutu rebels in Vugizo, in the troubled southern province of
Makamba of the central African state, reported Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Colonel Isaie Nibizi, the spokesman of the Tutsi-led
Burundian army, as saying that Hutu rebels called the villagers
out from their homes and killed them.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Hutu rebels are continuing to infiltrate from
neighboring Tanzania into southern Burundi's Kabonga and
Nyanza-Lac regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the governor of Makamba, Gilbert Manirambona, said
today that fierce fighting took place between government forces
and the rebels this week in Vugizo, destroying several hundred
houses and forcing several hundred civilians to flee home.
</P>
<P>
He told Radio Burundi that some 1,000 displaced people are now
living in a church in the town of Makamba.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian organization Medecins sans Frontieres said
that 1,000 other people have fled from Vugizo to the neighboring
village of Mabanda bordering Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian Defense Ministry said on Sunday that 140 rebels
and three government soldiers were killed in fighting in Mabanda
last week.
</P>
<P>
But the Hutu rebels of "National Council for the Defense of
Democracy" denied the report and said that the 140 people killed
were civilians.
</P>
<P>
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya said on Thursday that he had
raised the issue of rebel infiltration with Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa at a regional summit in Arusha, Tanzania, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At least 150,000 people, most of them civilians, have been
killed in ethnic violence and fighting in Burundi over the past
three and a half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
