<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Council Approves EU/US Deal on Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Council of the European
Union has approved on Friday the U.S.-EU deal on trade with Cuba,
Iran and Libya, formally announcing the suspension of EU's World
Trade Organization complaint against the U.S. Helms-Burton Act.
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called Understanding, hashed out in telephone
negotiations a week ago, EU's suspension would be rewarded by a
promise from the Clinton administration to work with Congress over
the next six months to protect European companies from the trade
sanctions in Helms-Burton legislation and the D'Amato Acts, which
seeks to penalize foreign investment in Iran and Libya's oil and
gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
The deal also calls for the two sides to negotiate a common
policy on properties seized by the Cuban government after the 1959
revolution, and try to globalize "strong standards" on protecting
property rights.
</P>
<P>
The EU Council warned that the European Commission would resume
WTO Panel or launch new WTO procedure if commitments to amend
Title III or Title IV of Helms-Burton legislation were not
respected by the US, or if waivers were not granted or withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
The Title III allows naturalized US citizens to sue foreign
firms suspected of profiting from disputed properties in Cuba
while the Title IV bars executives of these companies from
entering the United States.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU Council reiterated in a statement its "strong
opposition " to the imposition of extraterritorial legislation as
a means of advancing foreign policy objective.
</P>
<P>
"It considers such legislation to be unacceptable both in law
and in principle," the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
