<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 33 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-three rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in recent
operations launched by the Turkish security forces in southeastern
Turkey, an official statement said today.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule said that the Turkish government troops wiped out 15 PKK
militants in Eruh town of Siirt province, eight in Elmadag region
of Sirnak province bordering northern Iraq, four in Sehi forests
of Bitlis province, four in Kigi town of Bingol province and two
in Kozluk town of Batman province.
</P>
<P>
Six PKK militants surrendered to the security forces in the
region, said the statement. However, the statement failed to
disclose the date when the PKK guerrillas were killed in the
operations.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 12-year-old separatist war for
autonomy, which has claimed more than 21,000 lives including PKK
rebels, civilians and government troops in east and southeast
Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebel Leader Insists on Mobutu's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader Laurent
Kabila today reiterated his alliance's position that President
Mobutu Sese Seko must step down, otherwise rebel forces will march
on to the capital Kinshasa, a latest report available here said.
</P>
<P>
"The South African initiative is about transfer of power. When
he (Mobutu) is ready for this, I shall go and attend a short
day's ceremony on the peaceful transfer of power," Kabila was
quoted by the report as saying in Zaire's second largest city
Lubumbashi.
</P>
<P>
He added, "there will be no protracted negotiations with
Mobutu, never, never. The issue is about transfer of power,
otherwise we march on to Kinshasa."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebels now appear to be building up forces for
a possible assault on the Zairean capital.
</P>
<P>
No official response has so far been available from the Muboto
government on today's bombshell remarks of Kabila. But Mobutu's
son and spokesman Nzanga Mobutu confirmed on Thursday that his
66-year-old ailing father was ready to meet Kabila but refused to
step aside from power.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu's departure would bring chaos to Zaire, Nzanga said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila went to Cape Town of South Africa on Wednesday to hold
talks with President Nelson Mandela on the Zairean crisis. Later
on, Mandela also held discussions on the same issue with Mobutu's
special envoy Honore Nganda.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, South African Deputy Foreign Affairs
Minister Aziz Pahad announced at a news conference in Cape Town
that Mandela had formally invited Mobutu to meet Kabila
"as soon as possible" for talks in South Africa and the talks are
likely to take place "early next week".
</P>
<P>
The rebels took up arms to topple President Mobutu last
October. In less than six months, Kabila's Alliance of
Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) has
captured more than half of the territory of the third largest
country in Africa. 
</P>
