<HEADLINE> Decision on Indictment Against Netanyahu Due </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- State Attorney Edana Arbel
today said she would announce her decision Monday on the police
recommendation to indict Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu for
his role in the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
Arbel told Israel Radio that she had already made the decision
after consulting with Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein, and
would publicize it Monday evening before the Jewish holiday
Passover begins.
</P>
<P>
She described the decision as a very difficult one, for which
she would take full responsibility, but she declined to release
any detail.
</P>
<P>
The police team investigating the so-called "Bar-On for
Hebron" scandal recommended the state prosecution to indict
Netanyahu as well as Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime
Minister's Office Director-General Avigdor Liberman and Shas party
leader Aryeh Deri.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Hanegbi and Liberman were reportedly charged with
breach of trust in appointing former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On
as the attorney-general in January.
</P>
<P>
Deri was said to be charged with blackmailing in pushing for
Bar-On's appointment by threatening to vote against the Hebron
agreement which Netanyahu wanted so much to get it approved by
the cabinet on January 18.
</P>
<P>
By getting Bar-On appointed, Deri hoped to gain a favorable
plea bargain deal in his three-year long bribery trial. Ironically,
Bar-On resigned after one day in office only because of the public
criticism of his inadequate qualification and political
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
The police recommendation of corruption charges against
Netanyahu has triggered wide responses in Israel attracted
attention from the outside world as well. All eyes are now
focusing on the State Attorney's Office, which is to decide the
fate of the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties Labor and Meretz intensified their campaign
today to topple the government by holding a demonstration outside
the Prime Minister's Office to demand Netanyahu to resign
immediately. Dozens of Likud supporters also staged a
counter-demonstration at the same site to voice support to
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's aides have predicted that the prime minister would
escape any indictment because of the insufficient evidence
against him in the police recommendation. They pointed out that
the police recommendation were based on only one witness, and
Netanyahu was only questioned once during the three-month
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Arbel will only endorse the police suggestions when she thinks
that the evidence gathered so far can stand at the court of law.
</P>
<P>
Hinting that Netanyahu would likely not be indicted, Arbel
reportedly said the prime minister would not be questioned for
second time in future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
