<HEADLINE> Lebanon Marks 1996 Massacre at Qana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 18 (Xinhua) -- On the first anniversary of the
killing of 109 Lebanese civilians by Israel at the southern
Lebanese city of Qana, Lebanon today vowed that it will continue
fighting the Israeli occupation of Lebanon's land "in all
available forms and possible styles."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in the southern Lebanese port city of Sour,
Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berri stressed that "the resistance
is a natural result of the occupation and the peace weapon of
Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
"The resistance will not stop until all our national land is
liberated," he said. "The resistance will take all available
forms."
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery shelled a Fijian contingent camp of the
U.N. peacekeeping force in Qana, some 90 kilometers south of
Beirut, on April 18, 1996, making the day the bloodiest during
Israel's Grapes of Wrath operation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
To mark the massacre, a rally was held in an ancient Roman
stadium in Sour and attended by government ministers,
parliamentarians, religious leaders, foreign diplomats and
some 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Berri expressed a fear that a "heavy armament of
Israel by the United States' will encourage the Jewish state to
always resort to violence."
</P>
<P>
"As long as Israel wants to kill our children, we have to be
candid that the problem is not only with Israel, but was and still
is with the United States and its policy," the house speaker said.
</P>
<P>
"The commemoration of the Qana massacre opens a room to
remember that it was the most advanced artilleries made in the
U.S. which were used by the Israeli army in shelling the post of
the Fijian contingent in Qana where 990 Lebanese citizens were
sheltered in," the house speaker pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"This crime is the ugliest in the modern military history,
which, with other massacres that took place previously, invites a
reconsideration of the armament of the Israeli army by the
U.S. and the utilization of the U.S. weapons (by Israel) against
civilians," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sharply attacking the recent twin vetoes by Washington at the
U.N. Security Council against draft resolutions condemning
Israel's settlement activities in Arab East Jerusalem, Berri said
that the U.S. move encourages Israel to build more settlements and
resort to more violence.
</P>
<P>
After the rally, Berri and other officials went to the cemetery
of the Qana massacre's victims in the town and laid wreaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
