<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bomb Threats Affects Major's Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- When there are just 13 days left
before British voters go to the polling stations, Prime Minister
John Major's election campaign is shadowed by repeated IRA bombing
threats and explosions.
</P>
<P>
Two bombs blasted this morning in northern England cities,
Doncaster and Leeds, forcing police to seal off the city centers.
Police had also carried out a controlled explosion on a package at
Stoke rail station in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the explosions, rail and road traffic in northern
England was also totally blocked after police received telephoned
bombing threats this morning and closed a large section of major
highway M6 and four railway stations.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist actions appeared to be the latest attempt by the
Irish Republican Army (IRA) guerillas to disrupt Britain's
election campaign since Prime Minister Major was due to visit a
sports stadium near the closed section of the M6 highway today to
meet local voters.
</P>
<P>
This has reminded people of a huge explosion in London's
financial district in 1992 on the day that Major was re-elected.
IRA has claimed responsibility for that blast.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has been fighting against British rule of Northern
Ireland over the past 26 years and has claimed responsibilities
for most of the terrorist attacks and bombing threats in the past.
It quit a 17-month cease-fire agreement in February last year and
resorted to bombings again on the mainland since then.
</P>
<P>
However, Major went ahead with his plans today to campaign in
the north but a bomb disposal squad was on hand throughout his
visit.
</P>
<P>
It was not the first time Major's campaign tour was disrupted
since he announced the election day on May 1 in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
On April 5, a bomb warning forced the cancellation of the Grand
National Horse Race when the prime minister was in the region. One
day earlier, IRA bombing alerts forced the closure of three
important highways, costing transport industry millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last month, two bombs exploded near Wilmslow railway station in
northwest England, and Major had to campaign under tight security.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Sinn Fein, the political Wing of the IRA, has
said it was unlikely the guerilla group would renew its cease-fire
before the general election. Sinn Fein has pinned hope for the
opposition Labor Party to win the election so that it could rejoin
the peace process in Northern Ireland. Labor officials has
promised to allow Sinn Fein to participate in the peace talks if
it gives up terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
Major, whose Conservative Party has ruled Britain over the past
18 years, is now lagging behind the Labor Party by around 20
percentage points and seems set to be replaced by Labor leader
Tony Blair in the May 1 election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
