<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Improvement of Greco-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government considers
that progress in Greco-Turkish relations will contribute to
settling the Cyprus problem, Cypriot Foreign Minister Yiannakis
Cassoulides said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with President of House
of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou, Cassoulides expressed his
welcome to a meeting in Malta earlier this week between high
ranking officials from the foreign ministries of Greece and
Turkey. He noted that understanding between Greece and Turkey is
at a preliminary stage, but has not yet reached any final
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the ongoing proximity talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides, the foreign minister said "current or
future discussions are not carried out on the basis of the
U.N. 1992 Set of Ideas. We have rejected them as a framework for
an overall agreement."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that he could not rule out the possibility of
discussing some of the concepts, contained in these ideas, such as
the idea of a Cyprus solution on the basis of a bizonal,
bicommunal federation and the notion of political equality.
</P>
<P>
The Minister explained that the Set of Ideas was brought to the
foreground by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash who wishes to
use them as a basis for discussion on a negotiated settlement in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel reiterated today
that various documents such as the High Level Agreements of
1977 and 1979, the U.N. 1992 Set of Ideas, as well as relevant U.N.
Security Council resolutions are on the negotiating table for a
settlement to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The High Level Agreements provide for a bicommunal, bizonal
federation in Cyprus, and the U.N. Set of Ideas deal with
the constitutional aspects, security and guarantee, territorial
adjustments, displaced persons and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides have entered the sixth week, during which
U.N. envoy Feissel had bi-weekly separate meetings with President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash in a bid to
prepare the ground for face-to-face negotiations by the mid of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops landed and seized 37
percent of the territory in the wake of an Athens-backed
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
