<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pandora's Box Opens for Netanyahu Government (I) (By Zhi Linfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- When Israeli police recommended
indicting Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu for his alleged
involvement in a political scandal, the Pandora's Box has opened
for the 10-month old Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
State Attorney Edana Arbel today said she had already made
a decision, but she still kept the whole Jewish state,
perhaps the whole world, in anxious waiting for the fate of
the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
The wait will not last long, as Arbel will announce her
decision Monday on whether to endorse the police recommendation,
which was resulted from a three-month long probe into the
so-called "Bar-On for Hebron" scandal.
</P>
<P>
An upheaval shook the Israeli political spectrum and the whole
nation as well Wednesday when it was revealed that the
police team investigating the Bar-On scandal had recommended
an indictment against Netanyahu, together with Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime Minister's Office Director-General Avigdor
Liberman and Shas party leader Aryeh Deri.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Hanegbi and Liberman were reportedly charged with
breach of trust and fraud for their roles in appointing
former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general in
January.
</P>
<P>
Deri was said to be charged with blackmailing in pushing
for Bar-On's appointment by threatening to vote against the
Hebron agreement that Netanyahu wanted to get approved by
the cabinet on January 18. By getting Bar-On being appointed,
Deri hoped to gain a favorable plea bargain deal in his
three-year-long bribery trial.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is now under tremendous pressure from both the
opposition and the public to resign to take responsibility.
But he has flatly ruled out his resignation, insisting that
he was innocent and blameless and would fight for his
political survival.
</P>
<P>
However, legal experts and analysts agreed that the police
recommendation had opened the Pandora's Box of troubles for
Netanyahu and his government, regardless of state attorney's
decision to indict him or not.
</P>
<P>
If Netanyahu is indicted, it is almost certain that his
government will not survive and would be forced to resign to
open the way for new elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pandora's Box Opens for Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legally speaking, Netanyahu has the following options to
choose if indicted: resigning to pave the way for new
election of only a prime minister within 60 days; taking a
legally permitted 100-day leave in order to clear the charges
against him at the court, but if he fails to do so within the
period then new elections will be held; remaining in power in hope
to gather full support from his cabinet and coalition partners so
to give him time to prove his innocence at the court.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli law, Netanyahu can remain in power even
if he is indicted, but the question is whether he can hold
together the whole coalition around him in such a crisis.
Some ministers and ruling partners have made it clear that
they would leave the tarnished government if Netanyahu is
indicted.
</P>
<P>
And even if Netanyahu wins full support from the coalition, the
opposition parties will press further to petition the High Court
of Justice to force him to resign. The court has already set a
precedent in 1993, when it ruled that an indicted minister should
resign.
</P>
<P>
If Netanyahu is not indicted, it still does not mean that
he is clear of all troubles. First, the opposition can
also appeal to the High Court on the state prosecution's
decision not to indict him, or request the state controller
to investigate the prosecution's decision.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, if Netanyahu escapes the indictment but the justice
minister and the director-general of his office do not. Then, once
again his fate may be in the hands of the coalition partners,
which might bring the government down by leaving it because of
the damage to the government's credibility.
</P>
<P>
Several lawmakers from the Third Way, one of the main ruling
partners, have said that they would withdraw support to the
government if a serious breach of public norms is found in
the Bar-On affair even if Netanyahu will not be formally
charged.
</P>
<P>
Yisrael Baaliya, another major ruling coalition partner, today
also convened an urgent meeting to discuss the situation. Party
leader Natan Sharansky declined to make any comment, but he made
it clear during the course of the investigation of the Bar-0n scandal
that he would leave the government if any minister is found to
have been involved in the affair.
</P>
<P>
Despite the enormous pressure and accusations, Netanyahu, with
his characteristics of fighting spirit, vowed to fight for his
survival. Speaking at a party rally Thursday, he confidently
predicted that he would lead the country well till the year
2000 and even beyond.
</P>
<P>
But at this point, Netanyahu's greatest misfortune is that he
is not in any way in control of the situation, and there is
nothing whatsoever he can do to influence the outcome of the
present drama. He, like the rest of the world, has to wait for the
final verdict on his fate, to be issued Monday by the State Attorney's
Office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
