<HEADLINE> Zambia to Cut International Telecommunication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will cut tariffs for
international telecommunication services usage by 10 percent to
30 percent beginning May 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
International call charge will be reduced by 30 percent while
those for COMESA (the Common Market for the Eastern and Southern
Africa) countries will drop by 10 percent, according to an
announcement by Zambia Telecommunications Company.
</P>
<P>
In addition, customers will get a 25 percent reduction by
placing international calls during the off peak rate periods.
</P>
<P>
The charge per minute to COMESA countries will be reduced to
2.5 U.S. dollars during peak periods from current 2.8 dollars
while the charge to Europe, the United States and India will drop
to 3.2 dollars per minute during peak periods from current 4.4
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the domestic call unit rate has been adjusted upwards
by 20 percent to 120 kwacha from current 100 kwacha (less than 10
U.S. cents). The national call charges attract 50 percent
reduction during off peak rate periods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
