<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: How Israeli Prime Minister is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Basic Law, which was
passed in 1992 and came into effect with the last elections on
May 29, 1996, contains several clauses pertaining specifically to a
situation in which the prime minister cannot function in his post.
</P>
<P>
One section refers in particular to a situation in which the
prime minister is accused of a crime of moral turpitude and can
be impeached without the Knesset (Parliament) being dissolved.
</P>
<P>
But there is no explicit requirement in the law that the prime
minister step down if indicted, or even convicted of a crime that
"carries with it disgrace" -- such as fraud and breach of trust,
the offenses allegedly committed by current Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu in the "Bar-On for Hebron" scandal.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the prime minister can be removed from office
in three ways:
</P>
<P>
1. By a majority of 61 out of 120 Knesset members, in which
case new elections are held within 60 days for both a new prime
minister and the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
2. By a special majority of 80 of 120 Knesset members, in which
case the Knesset serves out its full four-year term and only
elections for a new prime minister are held.
</P>
<P>
3. If the prime minister has been convicted of a crime of
moral turpitude, he can be impeached without dissolving the
Knesset by a simple majority of 61.
</P>
<P>
If the prime minister resigns, special elections are held just
for the premiership and the Knesset serves out its current term.
</P>
<P>
A criminal investigation of the prime minister can only be
carried out with the approval of the attorney-general, who is
also the only person authorized to hand the premier an
indictment. Charges against the prime minister must be heard in
Jerusalem District Court before a bench of three judges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
