<HEADLINE> Nigerian Finance Chief Defends Tight Monetary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The current tight monetary policy
stance of the Nigerian government, with an equally tight fiscal
policy, is aimed at achieving macro-economic stability and
sustained growth, Finance Minister Anthony Ani said today.
</P>
<P>
However, the money market would be reformed in order to make
it a full-fledged secondary market in securities and short-term
funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said while interest rates were being deregulated with the
cap removed, sectoral credit allocation would be eliminated, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum subsidy would eventually be removed when the
refineries are privatized, he added.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the external sector policy of the government,
Ani said that policies aimed at stemming the rising level of
disbursements through the adoption of market-determined exchange
rates were being pursued.
</P>
<P>
There are two exchange rates effective in Nigeria at present.
One is the official rate of one U.S. Dollar to 22 Naila, the
other is the market rate of one Dollar to about 85 Naila.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would strive to achieve consistency in
its macro-economic policies through the harmonization of fiscal
and monetary policies to attain the desired level of liquidity
and consequently stablize the exchange rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
