<HEADLINE> Export-Import Company to Be Launched to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Arab Organization for
Investment and Agricultural Development (AOIAD) considers the
launching of an Arab export-import company in a bid to boost the
trade exchanges among the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian daily Assabah today quoted Chairman of the AOIAD
Youssef Abdullatif as saying that the trade exchange among the
Arab states accounted only for 10 percent of the total Arab trade
exchange with foreign countries in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The trade exchange of farm products and foodstuffs among
the Arab countries did not exceed 10 percent of the total Arab
trade exchange, Abdullatif added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the low percentage to the inefficiency and the
high cost of the transport as well as the dominant belief among
the Arabs that foreign products are more competitive in terms of
quality and cheap prices compared with Arab products.
</P>
<P>
Abdullatif pointed out that there is a food shortage in the
Arab world due to negligence of agricultural investment that
constitutes just 9 percent of the total Arab investment.
</P>
<P>
The AOIAD based in Khartoum, the capital of Sudan, has
recently organized the first forum for enterprises in which the
AOIAD is a partner with the participation of investors from 11
Arab countries. 
</P>
