<HEADLINE> SDP Head Blasts Land Lease Law for Undermining Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Takako Doi, head of Japan's Social
Democratic Party (SDP), today criticized a revision of law for the
continued compulsory leasing of land in Okinawa for use by the
U.S. military, saying it undermines the Japanese Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech at a two-day convention of the SDP, Doi
said the revised legislation "violates property rights protection
under Article 29 of the Constitution and puts the status of the
U.S. military ahead of the Constitution", Kyodo News Service
reported.
</P>
<P>
Japan's House of Councillors (Upper House) approved the
government proposed Okinawa land bill on Thursday. The bill became
law as it has already passed the more powerful House of
Representatives (Lower House).
</P>
<P>
The enacted revision of the 1952 law ensures that the
U.S. forces can continue to legally use land scattered in 12
military facilities in Okinawa Prefecture, owned by some 3,000
people who refuse to renew the leases after they expire May 14.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious" that the special land law runs counter to the
spirit of Article 95 of the Constitution, Doi, also a lecturer of
the Constitution, said.
</P>
<P>
The SDP chief accused some 80 percent of Diet (Parliament)
members of voting in favor of the Special law. SDP voted against
the law Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Doi also called on the government to help reduce the
U.S. military presence in Okinawa and promote the island
prefecture's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa is home to 75 percent of all U.S. military facilities
in Japan. More than half of the 47,000 U.S. troops in Japan are
stationed in the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
