<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Speaker Questioned Over Hanbo Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors today questioned the
speaker of South Korea's parliament about whether he took money
from the scandal-hit Hanbo Steel Co. which collapsed under six
billion U.S. dollars of debt in January.
</P>
<P>
Kim is the highest level politician implicated in the Hanbo
loans-for-kickbacks scandal. In view of his status as head of the
legislative body, investigators visited him at his official
residence instead of summoning him to the prosecutors' office.
</P>
<P>
Kim is the first head of South Korea's legislature to be probed
by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
State prosecutors said earlier this week that Chung Tae-soo,
founder of Hanbo, the country's 14th largest conglomerate, told
them he had donated funds to help Kim's parliamentary election
campaign in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors suspect more politicians may have taken bribes
in exchange for government-controlled bank loans and have so far
called in 33 politicians for questioning. Most of them have
admitted receiving money from Hanbo.
</P>
<P>
Chung is on trial for bribery and other charges along with nine
others, including three long-time political allies of President
Kim Young-sam, for their involvement in the collapse of Hanbo Steel Co
-- the flagship of the Hanbo Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
