<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Zedong's Hometown Booming With Tourism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The hometown of the late Chinese
leader Mao Zedong is getting richer from tourists eager to eat
Mao's favorite foods and buy Mao-related souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
With the deepening of the reform and opening up, the residents
of Shaoshan Village in central China's Hunan Province are making
the most of the tourism resources that abound in Mao's hometown.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the village earned a total of over 100
million yuan in 1996, and the annual income per villager reached
5,200 yuan. More than a decade ago, the village's total yearly
income was less than 60,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In many of Shaoshan's restaurants and hotels, varieties of
food, tea and wine that were favored by the late leader are
served. A number of hotels and shops also sell souvenirs, such as
commemorative music tapes and discs, coins, watches, and badges
that bear Mao's likeness. Even handkerchiefs and T-shirts are
printed with Mao's portrait, or poems or sayings.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the village has received several hundred
thousand overseas visitors, including more than a dozen state
leaders and high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
Tang Ruiren, owner of the well-known "Mao's Hometown
Restaurant" which is located opposite the late leader's former
residence, said that she has received 300,000-plus visitors.
</P>
<P>
"I have branch restaurants in cities like Beijing, Guangzhou,
Harbin and Xi'an, and I'm quite well-off now," said Tang, who has
donated over 400,000 yuan to help orphans, poor students, elderly
people and disaster-stricken areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Zedong's Hometown Booming With Tourism (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While the individually-run tourism services are flourishing in
the village, the overall economy has also grown quickly.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the village has received some 1.5 million
travelers annually in the past few years. To help accommodate
guests, the village government spent 200,000 yuan to build a
hotel, which has a yearly income in excess of one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
It has also invested 650,000 yuan for parking lots in three
famous scenic spots, bringing in a total annual income of more
than 600,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the village spent 40 million yuan to build the Mao
Zedong Commemorative Park, which has packed 15 man-made scenic
sites that have some connection with Mao into a 18-hectare
area. The park earned 11 million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The rapid tourism growth has also given impetus to the
development of the village's agriculture. The government spent
more than two million yuan last year for agricultural
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
The growing area of high-quality rice in Mao's hometown
accounts for 60 percent of the total, and more than 200 tons of
quality rice go into the market every year from the village,
figures show.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 2,000 pigs and eight tons of fresh fish
were sold in the village last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
