<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek and Turkish Cypriots Exchange Visits as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Some 450 Turkish Cypriots today
crossed into the southern government-controlled areas for a
pilgrimage to Hala Sultan Tekke Mosque in Larnaca, on the
southeastern coast, on the occasion of the Muslim religious
festival of "Kurban Bairam."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots were greeted at the Ledra Palace
check-point in Nicosia by Greek Cypriots, carrying olive
branches.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriots also handed to their Turkish Cypriot
compatriots messages urging them to join forces in trying to
re-unite their homeland divided for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since 1974 that Turkish Cypriots
visited the government-controlled southern areas of the island.
</P>
<P>
The visit came as a good-will gesture on the part of the
Greek Cypriot side in the framework of on-going proximity talks
under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
The proximity talks, which began on March 10, are aimed at
breaking the current deadlock on Cyprus problem and paving the
way for the U.N.-proposed face-to-face negotiations between
leaders of the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Hala Sultan Tekke, located on the shore of Larnaca's Salt
Lake, was built in memory of Umm Haram, an aunt of Prophet
Mohammed and is considered one of the holiest Islamic shrines.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side has also promised, as a good-will
gesture on its part, to allow Greek Cypriots to visit the
monastery of Apostolos Andreas, at the Turkish-controlled
northern part of the island, on Greek Orthodox Faster Sunday, on
April 27.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Greek and Turkish Cypriots have been separated and are
not allowed to cross the Green Line, which is controlled by the
1,200-strong U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
