<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Driving Force of Port City's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Overseas capital rapidly injected
in Tianjin, a port city in north China, has become a driving force
of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment has witnessed double-digit growth in the
city annually since 1992. The local economy in the period has also
posted double-digit growth four years straight. The city has
attracted 16 billion US dollars up to last year. Registered
overseas-funded ventures totaled more than 10,000, of which two
thirds are in various industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment has been used to revitalize the state
industrial enterprises, many of which have been operating at a
loss since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Some 68 local enterprises have cooperated with overseas
partners, greatly improving the technical and financial
management. Some even escaped from the edge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Medium- and small-sized state enterprises also found their part
to play in the renovation drive -- producing parts and components
for major overseas-funded ventures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show a contingent of smaller factories found this an
effective way out of management deadlock. Some 42 companies which
produced parts and components for Japanese Honda Motors posted
sales totalling 220 million yuan. A pager ring producer obtained
70 million yuan-worth orders from US's Motorola.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies in recent years not only transplanted
brand-names into China, but also created new brands in China, thus
shortening the gap between local companies with overseas producers.
</P>
<P>
Job opportunities have also been created. The employees in
enterprises with overseas investment have exceeded more than
320,000 in Tianjin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
