<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Carry on Negotiations for Joining WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China will firmly and
unswervingly carry on negotiations for joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO), despite the 10-year-long process such talks
have already taken, a senior Chinese government official stated
here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a symposium on the WTO and China's service trade,
Chinese Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Long Yongtu, who is also the country's chief trade negotiator,
said that China's access to the WTO means that the world's largest
country characterized by a planned economy would be included in
the multilateral system of a global market economy.
</P>
<P>
For China and the whole world, it will take time to coordinate,
adjust, and fit to each other in this process, he noted, adding
that during the past decade China has scored rapid economic
development, so the whole world will need time to regard and
accept an increasingly prosperous China.
</P>
<P>
Long said that China will not turn itself into a free trade
zone after it becomes a member of the WTO, and that its
enterprises will not benefit immediately.
</P>
<P>
How to seize the opportunities will require China's own efforts,
he said, since a multilateral global trade system can only create
a stable and sound multilateral and legal environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
