<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Beijingers Turn to Stocks, Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Individual investors in the
Chinese capital opened more than 80,000 stock trading accounts in
the first quarter of this year, about 6.5 times the figure of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that stock turnover in Beijing totalled 51.32
billion yuan (about 6.18 billion US dollars) by the end of
February, which was 10.9 times that of a year ago. Financial
institutions here sold seven billion yuan in corporate and
treasury bonds between January and March.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that active trading in stocks and bonds has
slowed down the increase in bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding deposits at the financial system in Beijing
amounted to 448.41 billion yuan by the end of last month. The
quarterly increase of 3.94 billion yuan was 8.19 billion yuan less
than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that personal savings deposits of urban and
rural residents totalled 175.72 billion yuan by the end of March,
up 5.02 billion yuan over the start of the year, which was 10.09
billion yuan less than a year ago. The increase in the three-month
period was the smallest in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that the banking system had a total of
216.5 billion yuan in outstanding loans by the end of last month,
down 1.77 billion yuan from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey by the Beijing branch of the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China shows that the bonds sold in the first
three months were bought with money diverted from savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that Beijing reported a net money
supply of 440 million yuan in the January-March period, the
largest in the last five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
