<HEADLINE> Russia to Invest in Iran's Oil, Gas Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced here today that
Russia would invest directly in oil and gas sectors in the
Islamic republic despite U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Hojatollah Ghanimi-Fard, director
of the International Affairs of the National Iranian Oil Company
(NIOC), according to the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the Iranian Oil Ministry and the
Russian Gazprom Gas Company have signed agreements for
cooperation in the fields of oil and gas sectors during the visit
by Iranian Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri to Moscow
last week.
</P>
<P>
Ghanimi-Fard said that on the basis of these agreements,
Gazprom would invest directly in the gas fields, help increase
production capacity, refining, liquefication and transportation of
natural gas, and promote cooperation in upstream and downstream gas
industries in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also develop mutual cooperation in
other areas of interest, the Iranian official said.
</P>
<P>
However, the official gave no details about the agreements. He
did not mention how much the Russian company is going to invest
or when and where the cooperation will be launched.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he added, a consortium of two Russian oil
companies concluded a cooperation agreement with the NIOC for
drilling in territorial waters of Iran.
</P>
<P>
So far part of the technical data has been exchanged in this
field and the process will be completed by the end of this month,
the NIOC official added.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the NIOC and the oil company of
Tatarstan had also signed an agreement during Nateq-Nouri's visit
to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two sides will cooperate in joint
projects in upstream and downstream oil industries.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the fourth largest oil producer and the second biggest
oil exporter in the world, pumps out 3.8 million barrels of crude
oil per day (bpd) and exports 2.6 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Oil export earned the country 19.5 billion U.S. dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic republic has been under U.S. sanctions
since last August when U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a new
law to punish non-American companies investing annually 40 million
U.S. dollars or more in energy projects in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have proved little successful as the European
countries refused to follow suit on the ground that isolating Iran
would not help curb terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Iran was accused of sponsoring terrorism, but Tehran rejected
the charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
