<HEADLINE> Cash Trees to Bring Money to Yunnan Poor Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan province
is now allocating 420 million yuan of funds to launch a "Green
Poverty Relief Project."
</P>
<P>
The project plans to pull five million poor farmers out of
poverty by helping them plant nearly 27,000 ha of cash trees
through the next four years.
</P>
<P>
These poor farmers, living in 506 poor villages, accounted for
92 percent of the province's total poor population.
</P>
<P>
According to the local government, It's only one of a series of
poverty relief projects to be carried out in the province.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan province, with its advantageous climate, is suitable for
a cash forest. To ensure the success of the project, the
provincial government has sent thousands of technicians to these
poor towns to guide farmers.
</P>
<P>
The province, as a remote province with poor transport
facilities, has the largest poor population in the country.
</P>
<P>
China sets the poverty line at annual per capita income of 500
yuan and per capita grain quota at 300 kilograms. Calculated on
this basis, the country still has 65 million poor people.
</P>
</TEXT>
