<HEADLINE> Seven-Day Ultimatum Extended in S. Lenone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 19 (Xinhua) - The seven-day ultimatum given by
the Sierra Leone government to a group of Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) rebels holding Sierra Leone's ambassador in Guinea
and two officials of the Commission for the Consolidation of
Peace (CCP) has been extended "indefinitely".
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Hinga Norman told Xinhua in a telepone
interview here today that the ultimatum was also for those who
''continue to violate the ceasefire and the peace accord''.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he recently established contact with Colonel Sam
Bockari of the RUF who gave the assurance that the hostages were
safe and sound. Bockari is said to be the No. 2 man of the RUF.
</P>
<P>
''I warned Colonel Bockari that should any harm comes to the
abductees, the RUF group would be held responsible'', Norman said.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision to extend the ultimatum was
''encouraged'' by an increasing number of rebels who have
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leone envoy, Ambassdor Mohamed Diaby and seven
dissident officials of the RUF were kidnapped some three weeks
ago by a group of RUF fighters in far eastern Sierra Leone. The
group said it was opposed to the replacement of the RUF leader,
Corporal Foday Sankoh, who has been in Nigeria for about seven
weeks under unexplained circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Among the seven officials held are two RUF members, Fayia Musa
and Ibrahim Deen Jalloh, who are RUF representatives to the CCP,
set up to work out modalities for the implementation of the peace
accord signed in Abidjan last November. enditem

