<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebels Agrees to Release Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebels have agreed to
release 46 Lebanese they held as hostages in the southeastern
city of Lubumbashi and allow them to leave at any time, the
London-based Orient Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The radio monitored here quoted officials in the Lebanese
Embassy in South Africa as saying that a deal was concluded
Thursday on the release of the Lebanese nationals, who were
rounded up by followers of rebel leader Laurent Kabila at an
airport in Lubumbashi on April 10.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese spent six hours at the airport, waiting to
be airlifted to safety by a French chartered plane, before they
were put in captivity.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached between the rebels and representatives
of the Lebanese community in Zaire, stressed that the Lebanese
have the right to return to the city after stability was
restored there, Lebanese diplomatic sources said in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
They noted the Lebanese are to be evacuated by air from
Lubumbashi today. 
</P>
