<HEADLINE> World's Biggest Reclamation Project Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Nine companies have proposed
to undertake a project -- reclaiming 12,800 hectares of land from
the sea off the coast of Malaysia's northern State of Kedah.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad was today briefed on
the proposed project, said to be the biggest ever in the world, at
Alor Setar, capital of Kedah, about 460 kilometers north from
here, according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project will run parallel to the state's coast for
100 kilometers and will be one kilometer from the coast.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is scheduled for completion by the year 2020
at an estimated cost of 30 billion ringgit (about 12 billion U.S.
dollars), will provide the land needed for housing and small
towns.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz Ibrahim, Director-General of the National Hydraulic
Research Institute of Malaysia and the project's consultant, said
after briefing the Prime Minister, that the proposed project will
have no negative effect on the environment while preventing
coastal erosion and protecting the state's mangrove swamp.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz said sand for the reclamation project will come from
the sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
