<HEADLINE> Beijing Inflation Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China's capital Beijing
registered a consumer price index increase of 6.4 percent in the
first three months of this year, according to latest statistics
from the local commercial commission.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 8.3 percentage points lower than that in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index increased 5.5 percent during the period,
down 4.5 percentage points from last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the city enjoyed an abundant retail market
and completed retail sales of 24.09 billion yuan, up 6.9 percent
in real terms.
</P>
<P>
The commission attributed the falling inflation to the
effective macro-control measures adopted by the local
government. The prices for major agricultural products linked to
residents' daily life have dropped to the lowest point.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the impacting factors of both last year's inflation
and newly-adapted prices this year were lower than last year's.
</P>
<P>
The commission admitted that prices on services and housing are
still running at high levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
