<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (31-32) (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Annex III of the Sino-British Joint Declaration stipulates, "in
the case of old schedule lots, village lots, small houses and
similar rural holdings where the property was on June 30, 1984
held by, or, in the case of small houses granted after that date,
the property is granted to, a person descended through the male
line from a person who was a resident in 1898 of an established
village in Hong Kong, the rent shall remain unchanged so long as
the property is held by that person or by one of his lawful
successors in the male line."
</P>
<P>
In consideration of this provision and realities, the Basic
Law makes special provisions on the legitimate rights and
interests of the original residents of the "New Territories", and
the above-mentioned provision of Annex III of the Sino-British
Joint Declaration is written in full into Article 122 of Chapter 5
of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Question: What institutions will be established in the Hong
Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: With regard to the establishment of institutions in the
future Hong Kong SAR, the Basic Law follows two principles, First,
in accordance with the spirit of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration, no changes will be made unless such changes are
necessary, and no changes will be made if such changes are not
desirable. What is more, good elements of existing institutions
will be either assimilated or retained.
</P>
<P>
Second, given the characteristics of the Hong Kong SAR, there
will be neither a complete copying of the names of existing
institutions, nor a duplication of the mainland's people's
congress, procuratorate and judicial systems, nor a patterning
after its governmental structure.
</P>
<P>
The most important institutions of the Hong Kong SAR are: the
Chief Executive, the government, the Legislative Council and the
Court of Final Appeal. In addition, there are the Executive
Council as well as the Commission Against Corruption and the
Commission of Audit, both of which work independently and are
accountable to the Chief Executive. Under the Hong Kong SAR will
be a department of administration, a department of finance, a
department of justice and various bureaux, divisions and
commissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (31-32) (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (31-32)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What are the legitimate traditional rights and
interests of the original residents of the "New Territories"?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The legitimate traditional rights and interests of
people in the "New Territories" will be protected by the Hong Kong
SAR. Original residents of the "New Territories" refer to people
descended through the male line from a person who was in 1898 a
resident of an established village in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some Hong Kong people maintain that the rights and interests of
the original residents of the "new Territories" have been
inherited from common practices and customs of the Qing
Dynasty. In 1898 when Britain leased the "New Territories" by
force, it offered a series of conditions to the original residents
for purchasing land to expand the "New Territories".
</P>
<P>
These include:
</P>
<P>
1) The original male residents have the right to build family
</P>
<P>
houses (their male descendants may have the same right);
</P>
<P>
2) Village lots may be exempt from taxes to the government;
</P>
<P>
3) Compensation may be given for land exchanges and lease;
</P>
<P>
4) For village lots in renewal terms, only symbolic rent
</P>
<P>
needs to be paid; and
</P>
<P>
5) Residents are allowed to retain the right to traditional
underground burial in Fengshui land. These rights and interests
have remained unchanged in the form of government policies and
decrees.
</P>
<P>
A decision was made to allow holders of such traditional rights
to retain their rights during Sino-British negotiations in the
light of China's commitment to let Hong Kong "remain unchanged for
50 years."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
