<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
Tehran -- Amid crisis in relations between Iran and the EU
countries, the local newspapers urged the government to revise its
foreign trade policy toward the EU and not to put eggs in one
basket.
</P>
<P>
The English-dailies Iran News and Tehran Times in their
editorials today called on the Iranian leadership to seek closer
economic and trade ties with the East European and Asian
countries, making the Islamic republic less dependent on the EU
states.
</P>
<P>
Iran imports about 15-18 billion U.S. dollars worth of products
from the EU countries yearly.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus ranks fifth on the list of world merchant
shipping, with 2,733 vessels and a total of 26.15 million gross
tonnage.
</P>
<P>
It comes behind Panama, Liberia, Greece and the Bahamas in
terms of merchant shipping, according to the merchant shipping
authority here.
</P>
<P>
Direct revenues, such as taxes, resulting from Cyprus-flagged
vessels, reach 5 million Cyprus pounds per annum (about 10 million
U.S. dollars), while indirect revenues, including shipping
companies' payrolls, premise-rents, telecommunications expenses,
reach around 45 pounds (some 90 million dollars), the authority
disclosed this week.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Economy and International
Cooperation Nawal al Tatawy has disclosed that the international
reserves in the Central Bank reached 19.1 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He expected the country's gross domestic production growth rate
to reach 5.7 percent this year from 4.9 percent in 1996 and 1.9
percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate will drop to 6 percent this year from 7.2
percent of last year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign debt in December 1996 was about 30
billion dollars against 31.8 billion in December 1995. Egypt's
debt to the members of Paris Club is 24.1 billion to represent
84.2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Ministrer of Petroleum Hamdy El Banby said
that his country's crude oil production reached 880,000 barrels
per day plus about 1,600,000,000,000 cubic feet of natural gas
meeting about 92 percent of domestic needs.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Consumers spent 7.5 billion U.S. dollars in Turkey in
1996 using Visa International credit cards, up 285 percent from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Holders of the cards increased by 14 percent in Europe to over
100 million and Turkey ranks fourth in the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
