<HEADLINE> S. Africa Expects to Export Weapons to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Turkey are
preparing to boost arms deals after the former first lifted a ban on
weapons exports to the latter, the local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The decision (to lift the embargo) will only improve the
relations between the two countries," South African Ambassador to
Turkey Riaan Eksteen was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
There is a great potential of cooperation between South Africa
and Turkey, which should cover military and defense fields, the
ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa imformed Turkey on Tuesday that it had lifted the ban
and placed Turkey in a list of countries with no limitations on arms
exports.
</P>
<P>
In a positive reponse, the Turkish government has also invited
South Africa to bid for a huge helicopter deal.
</P>
<P>
Local defense sources said major South African arms exporter Denel,
which produces the advanced Rooivalks attack helicopters, has a
reasonable chance of winning the Turkish tender for up to 145
gunships.
</P>
<P>
South Africa imposed a ban on arms exports to Turkey in April
1995 after the Turkish Army invaded northern Iraq to hunt down
separatist Turkish Kurds who had bases in the area.
</P>
<P>
It at the time denounced the Turkish incursion as a violation of an
independent country's sovereignty. In retaliation, Turkey placed South
Africa in its red list of countries, banning all potential arms deals.
