<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Papers Urge Government to Revise Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian newspapers urged today the
government to revise its foreign trade policy toward European
countries and not put all its eggs in one basket.
</P>
<P>
The official English dailies Iran News and Tehran Times
published editorials entitled "Don't Put All the Eggs in One
Basket" and "Realistic Approach to Foreign Trade Vital."
</P>
<P>
Iran News said that Iran should expand its economic cooperation
and trade with East European countries to encounter a western
campaign spearheaded by the U.S. to isolate the Islamic republic.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation with Russia and Eastward trends in the Iranian
economy could be the best answer to Western plan against the
Islamic Republic," it said.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times commented in its editorial: "We must not create a
situation for our trade partners to use trade as a tool to
strangulate us."
</P>
<P>
"We must be very serious in diversifying the sources of our
foreign trade, for disproportionate dependence on a country or a
bloc of countries is tantamount to a 'commercial suicide' to us,"
it noted.
</P>
<P>
In the article, it urged the Iranian government to expand its
relations "with regional and Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
It also said in the editorial "In order to minimize the
chance of our partners to use trade as a pressure lever, our
policy makers must in the first instance review all our economic
plans and see if our plan can really lead us to self-sufficiency
and self-reliance."
</P>
<P>
Iran's relations with European countries have come into a
grave crisis and all ambassadors of the European Union (EU) states
except Greece were recalled shortly after the Berlin court ruled
on April 10 that the Iranian leadership was involved in the 1992
killing of four Kurdish dissidents in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Germany is now the leading trade partner of Iran after the
United States broke off diplomatic and economic ties with
Tehran 18 years ago. The total annual trade volume of Germany and
the Islamic republic once topped 4 billion U.S. dollars in the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
Germany takes a lionshare of Iran's total import and
export. Its export made up 41.3 percent while its import amounted
to 32.8 percent of Iran's total in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The EU imports to Iran total about 15-18 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran News noted that Iran and the EU have had what it called a
head-on collision following the Berlin court verdict which, Iran
believed, was politicized.
</P>
<P>
The editorial warned Iranian economists not to keep all Iran's
eggs in one basket, adding "We have to look toward the East to
balance our trade and economy."
</P>
<P>
It called on the decision-makers in the country to make more
specific and comprehensive planning on the matter. "In the Pacific
region, the most modern technology is available," it said.
</P>
<P>
"What is most important is that, unlike Europe, the Pacific
region has never shown sensitivity against Islam, a vital factor
that makes business with them easier," it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
