<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Not to Bow to Pressure by Donors, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin Amour
said on Friday that his government would not bow to pressure by donor
countries, many of which have suspended development aid to the Isles,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We have no business to woo donors who are reluctant to help us,"
Amour told an Idd El Haj Baraza at the House of Representative in the
town of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
He said donors' decision to suspend aid will under no
circumstances affect the Isles pace of development.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar president said donors should not dictate terms to
Zanzibar, insisting that people were the main players in bringing
development.
</P>
<P>
Amour's remarks were apparently in reaction to the recent European
Commission (EC) decision to freeze development aid to Zanzibar until
the prevailing political tension in Zanzibar is resolved and the human
rights record improved.
</P>
<P>
The political tension in Zanzibar arose after the 1995 presidential
elections when defeated Civic United Front (CUF) candidate, Seif
Shariff Hamad, claimed that the results were rigged and refused to
accept Amour as the legitimate leader.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Amour said he was aware that some Zanzibaris
devoted their time to convince donors to stop aids to the government
on grounds of lack of democracy but said the islands would shine star
despite suspension of aids to development.
</P>
<P>
He further said the government was aware of economic difficulties
facing the people but said hardworking and co-operation was a solution
to solve the snags.
</P>
<P>
He asked the people to maintain unity and peace asking them to
ignore political provocations aimed at disturbing unity and peace
there.  enditem

