<HEADLINE> E. African Speakers Want More Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Speakers of national assemblies
of Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda have recommended formation of a joint
committee of the three houses to promote East African Co-operation
(EAC).
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, the recommendation came out of a
one-day meeting of the speakers in Arusha, Northern Tanzania this week
under the framework of EAC.
</P>
<P>
They said the compostion and mandate of the joint committee would
be determined through appropriate consultations.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting it was considered pertinent that national
assemblies be closely associated with the process of the expanding
regional co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Secretary of the EAC, Francis Muthaura, told reporters
in Arusha on Friday that the meeting discussed how national
parliaments could be associated with the developments in the EAC.
</P>
<P>
He said, the speakers noted that the EAC was consistent with global
trend towards regional, political and economic integration as well as
enhancement of public accountability and pluralism.
</P>
<P>
"They highlighted the need to ensure that public opinion of EAC was
taken into account and in that regard, unanimously stressed the
importance of ensuring that political co-operation was developed
alongside economic co-operation as the two dimensions were
intertwined," Muthaura said.
</P>
<P>
He said that they noted political co-operation was therefore
necessary for sustenance of other aspects of co-operation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The respective speakers who attended the meeting were Pius Msekwa
of Tanzania, Francis Ole Kaparo of Kenya and James Wapakhabulo of
Uganda. enditem

