<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Achieve Higher Growth Next Year: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will try to
achieve a 9.5 percent GNP growth in 1998, much higher than the 7
percent projected by the Asian Development Bank (ADB) for the
country, said a senior official.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published here today, Socio-economic Planning
Secretary Cielito Habito said that realizing the goal requires
"more efforts to upgrade the country's infrastructure and
implementing policy reform agenda, particularly the comprehensive
tax reform package," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government also needs to continue its economic reforms such
as liberalization, deregulation and procuring more foreign direct
investments, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Philippines' gross national product (GNP) grew by
6.8 percent and gross domestic product (GDP) by 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In its annual economic outlook report released here Thursday,
ADB said that growth in the country's GNP is expected to level off
at 7 percent in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
But Habito said that the country could achieve a higher growth
rate as the acceleration of the Philippine economy remains in the
uptrend.
</P>
<P>
However, Habito said, the Philippines cannot achieve the status
of the newly industrializing economy (NIE) by the year 2000
because his country's per capita income still falls short of the
2,000 U.S. dollars or above required to become an NIE.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, ADB, in its annual report, cited only Hong Kong, South
Korea, Singapore and China's Taipei, as NIEs in the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Habito said that as of 1996, the Philippines' per capita income
was at 1,200 dollars and the government will try to raise it to
1,400 dollars to 1,500 dollars by 1998 and 1,700 dollars to 1,800
dollars by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
