<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Pan Africanist Congress
(PAC) of South Africa is to continue its disciplinary action against
its former president Clarence Makwetu today in Pretoria for three
alleged violations of party's constitution, reported the local daily
Saturday Star.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu, who earlier this month was suspended by the PAC's National
Executive Committee (NEC) as party's national chairman and NEC member,
indicated he would attend the hearing at PAC's Pretoria office, a
party spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu is facing three charges relating to allegations that he has
divided the party, created factions, and has violated the PAC's oath
of allegiance which states that a member will accept party leadership.
</P>
<P>
In spite of his absence from the first hearing, the disciplinary
committee went ahead with its inquiry on April 3.
</P>
<P>
PAC insiders said at the time the disciplinary committee had
recommended to the NEC that Makwetu be suspended and given another
opportunity to defend himself, to counter accusations by Makwetu's
supporters that he had not received a fair hearing, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu lost the presidency to former Methodist Bishop Stanley
Mogoba at the PAC's national conference in December last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Makwetu's supporters claim that the elections were
unconstitutional and have refused to recognise the party's new
leadership, thus causing an internal strife and rival factions.
