<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Australian, New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian Foreign Ministry
hailed the return of Australian and New Zealand ambassadors to
Tehran after "consultations" with their respective governments, an
official report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, termed
their return as positive and important in the relations between
Iran and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Iran will consider the move by the two countries in the future
relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that by sending their ambassadors back to
Tehran, Australia and New Zealand would separate their interests
from those of the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors of Australia, Canada and New Zealand,
non-member states of the European Union (EU), went home last week
for "consultations" in line with EU states after the Berlin court
ruled early this week that top Iranian leaders were involved in the
1992 killing of four Kurdish dissidents.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries, except Greece, recalled their ambassadors to
Iran shortly after the Berlin court handed down the verdict on
April 16. Iran rejected the ruling and called its ambassadors back
home in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Australia, Canada and New Zealand wasted no time to echo the
EU, an action further outraging Iran.
</P>
<P>
In response to Wellington's move, Tehran had announced that it
would stop buying meat, butter and wool from New Zealand. Iran is
also a substantial importer of Australian wheat and meat.
</P>
<P>
Australian Ambassador Stuart Hume and New Zealand Ambassador
John Hayes flew back to Tehran Friday,according to local press
reports. But they could not be reached for comment so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
