<HEADLINE> Central Nepal Faces Power Shortage This Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's capital city and other
parts of central Nepal are facing frequent load shedding this
summer as two hydroelectric stations are set to stop operation
next week, sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
The electricity authorities have decided to impose load
shedding on a rotatory basis to limit the consumption of
electricity in central Nepal when Kulehkani Project I and Project
II close due to the construction of a new sloping intake, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The Kulehkani Hydroelectric Project, located some 50 km south
of Kathmandu, is a major power supplier in central Nepal with its
two generating stations totaling over 90 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a new intake tunnel on the reservoir for
Kulehkani project has started earlier with a view to preventing
possible disaster, project officials said.
</P>
<P>
Engineers feared that an old intake on the reservoir would be
clogged in the future as the reservoir has been filled up to a
height of some 28 meters due to soil, sand and stones accumulated
since the project went into operation nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The project will resume power-generating in full capacity late
this summer when the reservoir is filled with rain water of this
year's monsoon season, they said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal at present has a total installed generating capacity of
nearly 300 megawatts and some 85 percent of the country's 20
million people still have no access to electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
