<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) staged a strong recovery at the end
of this trading week but analysts said the rebound should not be
taken as a signal that the bearish sentiment of the past three
weeks was over.
</P>
<P>
For the week just ended, investors on the KLSE went through a
harrowing experience with many having got "their fingers burnt" as
share prices took a severe setback when Wall Street nose-dived on
April 11.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index slipped 33.78 points to end the week at
1,104.58, the Emas Index eased 11.15 points to 318.25 while the
Industrial Index fell 55.4 points to 2,083.85.
</P>
<P>
Institutions abstained from accumulating shares aggressively as
local economic fundamentals had changed with the implementation of
the National Bank's latest lending curbs.
</P>
<P>
Foreign fund managers were sidelined as the flattering ringgit,
which tumbled close to 200 basis points over the previous week,
did not provide much incentive for them to invest in the bourse.
</P>
<P>
The week saw the listing of two new counters, Rubberex
Corporation (Malaysia) Bhd (Limited) and Seacorp-Schroder
Smallcap Fund Bhd (Limited).
</P>
<P>
Rubberex opened at 7.00 ringgit (about 2.8 U.S. dollars) but
ended the week at 6.85 ringgit (about 2.74 U.S. dollars) while
Seacorp opened below its issue price of 1.00 ringgit (about 40
U.S. cents), at 0.80 ringgit (about 32 U.S. cents) per share, but
managed to end the week higher at 0.92 ringgit (about 36.8 U.S.
cents).
</P>
<P>
Mainboard turnover totaled 1.177 billion shares valued at 7.021
billion ringgit (about 2.8084 billion U.S. dollars) against 1.207
billion shares worth 7.008 billion ringgit (about 2.8032 billion
U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Second board volume totaled 189.277 million shares worth 1.907
billion ringgit (about 762.8 million U.S. dollars) against last
week's 203.042 million shares valued at 2.213 billion ringgit
(about 885.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off market deals amounted to a weekly volume of 141.959 million
shares valued at 1.192 billion ringgit (about 476.8 million U.S.
dollars) compared with 235.994 million shares valued at 1.702
billion ringgit (about 680.8 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The top ten active counters this week were Kuala Lumpur
Industries Holdings which fell 30 sen to 3.28 ringgit on a
turnover of 45.244 million shares, Aokam Perdana erased 16 sen to
3.32 ringgit with 43.157 million shares traded, Chase Perdana Bhd
fell 30 sen to 10.20 ringgit (31.768 million shares traded),
North Borneo Timber gained 1.70 ringgit to 20.90 ringgit (26.760
million shares traded), Renong reduced six sen to 3.72 ringgit
(23.395 million shares traded), Sinora fell 1.40 ringgit to 17.30
ringgit (22.540 million shares traded), B-Industrial lost 12 sen
to 3.00 ringgit (22.279 million shares traded), Tekala gave up 80
sen to 5.70 ringgit (21.659 million shares traded), Suria Capital
shed one sen to 2.80 ringgit (18.374 million shares traded) and
Samanda erased 70 sen to 14.70 ringgit (15.507 million shares
traded).
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 102.416
million shares traded, industrial products 241.169 million shares,
construction 92.688 million shares, trading/services 169.385
million shares, infrastructure 1.941 million shares, finance
129.516 million shares, hotels 24.806 million shares, properties
199.542 million shares, plantation 85.593 million shares, mining
12.413 million shares, trusts 2.736 million shares, loans 20.593
million shares, call-warrants 80.013 million shares and closed
funds 13.359 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said stock market investors should approach the KLSE
with cautious optimism next week.
</P>
<P>
They said if the index can break the next resistance level of
1,175 points, then this could signal the return of an upward trend
and the entry of foreign funds in a big way.  
</P>
</TEXT>
