<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
mixed. All the markets were closed Friday following Moslems'
religious festival of sacrifice (Corban).
</P>
<P>
During the week, the CPO physicals market remained volatile
following uncertainties in the market but surged Thursday on some
late pre-weekend short-covering activity.
</P>
<P>
April South gained 20 ringgit (about 8 U.S. dollars) to close
the week at 1,325 ringgit (about 530 U.S. dollars) per ton against
1,305 ringgit (about 522 U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Wong, a private forecaster, said during the week that
March's palm oil output was expected to rise 32 percent to
665,000 tons from February production.
</P>
<P>
He estimated end-March stock level at about 725,000 tons
against February revised stock level of 722,993 tons as announced
by the Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority (PORLA).
</P>
<P>
The CPO market is expected to hover around current price levels
next week despite the absence of a clear market direction, a
dealer said, adding prices were not likely to drop next week as
the commodity was still enjoying good demand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was also volatile
during the week with prices moving in tandem with the London Metal
Exchange (LME) which moved up and down throughout this week.
</P>
<P>
The metal lost five sen to end the week at 14.05 ringgit (about
5.62 U. S. dollars) per kg following the significant fall in the
price of three-month tin on the LME.
</P>
<P>
Turnover this week eased to 443 tons from 449 tons last week
with local and European buyers accounting for the bulk of
transactions.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is expected to experience choppy trading next week
following the uncertainty on the LME, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the Malaysian rubber market was bearish and
the poor performance in the Tokyo rubber futures market coupled
with lower advice from regional markets of Thailand and Indonesia
also dampened market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
May International RSS One dipped three sen to close the week at
287.50 sen (about 115 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 fell 4.5 sen
to 270.50 sen (about 108.2 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for April 16 stood at 218.42
Malaysia/Singapore cents (sen) per kg against 221.64 cents (sen)
on April 10.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 220.39 cents per kg versus
222.86 cents previously.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber market is expected to continue its downtrend
next week in the absence of fresh market moving factors and a
clear direction, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The market is currently void of any fundamental developments to
support the bearish market and against this background, players
are expected to adopt a wait-and-see attitude, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
