<HEADLINE> Delhi City Authorities Urged to Clear Stray Cattle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Delhi High Court has
ordered the city authorities to clear the roads of stray cattle in
order to avoid traffic jams and accidents, the Times of India said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a front-page story, the newspaper said the Delhi High Court
has issued notice to the city government and to various local
bodies on a petition seeking removal of stray cattle and other
animals because they are a traffic hazard.
</P>
<P>
Advocate B.L. Wadehra contended in his petition that thousands
of cows, calves, bulls, pigs and other such animals are let loose
by their owners to roam around the city during the day.
</P>
<P>
These animals, he said, often end up on busy roads, lanes,
parks and markets and cause traffic jams and accidents besides
pillaging fruits and vegetable shops and leading to insanitary
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The petitioner argued that according to local legislation, it
is the statutory duty of the local authorities, including the city
government, to keep the city clear of such wandering animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
