<HEADLINE> Italian Minister Tight Mouthed on Islamic Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian Interior Minister Giorgio
Napolitano said today that he could not confirm or deny a military
intelligence report leaked to the Italian press about Islamic
terrorist threats against Pope John Paul II, and to major Italian
airports.
</P>
<P>
But he denied attending a security summit on Wednesday night at
which the report was said to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The minister also denied saying security measures had been
tightened at major international airports in Milan and Rome.
</P>
<P>
Those who spread the alarm could only harm the cause of public
security, Napolitano said. "The threat of terrorism has been there
for some time in Italy, as in other European countries, and
vigilance in the face of any possible threat is permanent and
systematic."
</P>
<P>
The report of the military intelligence agency, Sismi, was
leaked to the Italian news agency Ansa on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Islamic terrorists were plotting to
assassinate the Pope. The plot was said to be linked to the
weekend mining of a Sarajevo bridge the Pope was to pass over and
to the diplomatic crisis between the European Union and Iran after
a Berlin court found Iranian officials responsible for ordering
the murders of Kurdish opposition leaders in a Berlin restaurant
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Leonardo da Vinci international airport was put
on maximum alert today.
</P>
<P>
Airport sources said security measures have been tightened,
especially for United States and Middle Eastern airlines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
