<HEADLINE> Mongolia Passes New Tax Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ulan Bator, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Great Hural (parliament)
of Mongolia today passed laws to eliminate import taxes on most
commodities while doubling that on special or luxurious items.
</P>
<P>
Under the new laws, the government will not levy on most
imported items starting from May 1, except cars, oil products,
liquors, cigarettes and other special or luxurious commodities.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's economy in the first quarter of the year continued
the downtrend that started in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Statistics Bureau, Mongolia recorded a
budget deficit of 5.8 billion togrog (about seven million
U.S. dollars) while its industrial output stood at 44.1 billion
togrog (53.4 million dollars), 4.8 percent down from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said the average monthly increase of price index was
2.7 percent, and about 60,800 people -- 5.12 percent of Mongolia's
labor force-- were registered jobless by April 1, or 5,364 more
than the total by the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
