<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's C. America Trip Aims to Consolidate Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton's visit to Central America aims to support the creation of
an Americas free trade area, the U.S. Ambassador to Costa Rica,
Peter Jon de Vos, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to arrive here on May 7. He will meet the
presidents of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras and
Guatemala, the five Central American countries, and the president
of the Dominican Republic and the Belize prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Central American countries are willing to create a forum to
discuss regional problems with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The summit will focus on economic and commercial issues. The
Central American countries want to substitute the trade benefits
given them by the project of the Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI)
with others granted by international agreements which cannot be
revoked unilaterally by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The CBI was initiated by former U.S. President Ronald Reagan as
part of his strategy of war against the Sandinista government of
Nicaragua in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said the Clinton administration sent to
Congress a project directed to extend the benefits of the CBI.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said of most importance to the
U.S. government was the creation of better conditions for private
investments in Central America, and a new strategy to simplify
conditions for private capital.
</P>
<P>
The Central American countries said a free trade agreement
with the United States would guarantee investors more security in
access to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
But "it has not been determined how we are to advance in the
creation of the free trade area," de Vos said.
</P>
<P>
He said that besides the commercial theme, other proposals
worked out by the presidents of the hemisphere in the summit held
in Miami in December 1994, such as the war against drug
trafficking and terrorism, sustainable development, environmental
protection, democracy and a policy of open skies, would also be
discussed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
