<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Tried in Peru for Plane Crash in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Five workers of the Aeroperu airline
will be tried to determine the degree of their responsibility in
an airliner accident in October 1996 which killed 70 persons.
</P>
<P>
The Prosecutorship of Lima said the five workers are
responsible for the crash of a Boeing 757 on October 2 of 1996 in
the sea off the coast of Chancay, north of Lima.
</P>
<P>
According to the charges filed by the prosecutorship, the
accident was caused by a human error, since the workers did not
retire opportunely the adhesive tapes they had closed the static
ports with, which affected the speedometer and the altimeter of
the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutorship also blamed the pilot, who did not execute
the procedure of using the system of auditive alarms nor noticed
the deficiency in the lecture of the instruments.
</P>
<P>
The five workers will be sanctioned with penalties of two to
six years in prison if their responsibilities are
established. 
</P>
</TEXT>
