<HEADLINE> Italy Complains About Albanian Election Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta complained today about setting the date for Albanian
election on June 29, saying it will bring Italy "heavy financial
burden and human risks".
</P>
<P>
Talking with Franz Vranitzky, special envoy for the
Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to
Albania, Andreatta said public opinion in Italy will "not allow us
to keep forces abroad, which involve a heavy financial burden and
human risks."
</P>
<P>
Italy leads a 6,000-strong multinational protection force,
which started spreading out throughout Albania Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the minister admitted that a clearly-fixed date for the
election is essential for international community to pursue its
commitment, "with human and financial resources, to the rebirth of
Albania".
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky, also former Austrian Chancellor, pressed the
Albanian political parties in Tirana Thursday to set the June 29
date for emergency parliamentary election aimed at moving this
anarchic country toward stability.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Europe want to help the Albanian people with all
their might and now it's the duty of the Albanians to commit
themselves in that direction," Vranitzky said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the multinational force, contributed by eight
European nations, Andreatta said there will be 3,500 to 4,000
troops deployed in the country by Monday.
</P>
<P>
"About two-thirds of the force will be deployed ahead of
schedule and command headquarters in Tirana will be up and
running," the defense chief added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
