<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Prevents Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin province
is taking new measures to prevent forest fire, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 forestry-conservation workers have been
positioned to keep round-the-clock observation of the woods around
the Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The province has 7.6 million ha of forest, and so is vulnerable
to big blazes, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
With temperatures getting warmer and dry weather continuing,
local forestry officials are now on red alert and have warned that
fires have broken out in the southeast and northwest areas of the
province. However, they were quickly put out.
</P>
<P>
Research is under way using new technology that may help to
prevent and put out fires in the future.
</P>
<P>
The province has also enforced new regulations, which include
a ban on fires to make picnic lunches.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry will invest 5.4 million yuan to
support the province's forestry fire prevention campaign this
year, up one third over last year.
</P>
<P>
The neighboring Heilongjiang province has also redoubled their
efforts to prevent forest fire, according to another source.
</P>
<P>
China has succeeded in the prevention of major forest fires for
almost ten years since the disastrous fire in northeast China Da
Xinggan Mountain in 1987, which wiped out five percent of
China's total forested area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
