<HEADLINE> FIFA to Investigate World Cup Bribery Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The soccer's world governing body
said on Friday that it would investigate allegations of bribery in
a World Cup qualifier between Switzerland and Norway.
</P>
<P>
The scandal was unveiled when UEFA investigated Swiss referee
Kurt Roethlisberger for allegedly trying to fix a European
Champions' league match between Grasshopper Zurich and Auxerre.
</P>
<P>
He was suspended for life on March 27.
</P>
<P>
Blick, a Swiss-German tabloid, claimed Roethlisberger offered
to fix the match for the favour of the Swiss at a price of 100,000
Swiss Francs (68,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Blick said the offer was made four days before the World Cup
qualifier in Switzerland, which Norway won 1-0.
</P>
<P>
"In the beginning it was just something between Roethlisberger
and a Swiss newspaper but now, after reviewing the UEFA documents,
it is something FIFA wants to look into since it was a World Cup
match," FIFA spokesman Andreas Herren said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
