<HEADLINE> Three European Blocs Get Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Northern, eastern and central
European countries today vowed to promote ties between themselves
in "a new form of North-South cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Three subregional European blocs, the Central European
Initiative (CEI), grouping 16 central and eastern European
countries; the Black Sea Economic Cooperation forum, embracing 11
Black Sea countries, and the Council of the Baltic Sea States,
with 11 Baltic countries, today held their first official joint
meeting in Trieste in northeastern Italy.
</P>
<P>
Countries across the continent from Germany and Sweden to
Turkey, Bosnia, Latvia, Ukraine and Russia discussed cooperation
in transport, finance, energy and fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The CEI duty chairman, Mahir Hadziah from Bosnia, said the
meeting marked the beginning of a new form of North-South
cooperation, as it involves former Soviet republics which are
applying for membership of the European Union and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization. 
</P>
