<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yellow River Runs Short Of Water At Lower Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China's Yellow River has run short
of water at its 786-km lower reaches for the twentieth year since
1972, and experts are racking their brains to think of ways to
make it run at full level again.
</P>
<P>
The 5,464-km river, China's second-longest next to the Yangtze
River, is the cradle of the Chinese culture and plays an important
part in the country's national economic development.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in the 1990s, conditions in the river worsened. The
period of no water at the lower reaches stretched into 136 days in
1996, and 87 percent of the lower reaches' courses ran short of
water in 1995.
</P>
<P>
More areas along the river are suffering from this, according
to the Yellow River Water Conservancy Committee.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the time when the river runs short of water at its
lower reaches happened at a much earlier date this year. In the
past it came between April and June, the water-consuming peak
seasons, but this year it occurred on February 7.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the situation to increased water use along
the river. By 1995, 122 projects diverting water from the river
were built at its lower reaches, with a total capacity of 4,000
cubic meters per second, far exceeding the river's possible water
supply of 58 billion cm annual runoff.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the river's annual runoff comes between
July and September, while less than 20 percent runs into the river
from April to June. Insufficient water supply has caused nearly
1.4 billion yuan-worth of economic losses over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Areas along the river should give top priority to saving water
and can also make use of groundwater to ease the river's
pressure. Water control projects on the middle reaches are needed
to improve the river's ability of regulating its water flow and
silt, experts suggested.
</P>
<P>
Diverting water from south China into the river is another
option. But the ultimate answer is to develop forestry in the
river valley, in a bid to improve its ecological environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 53rd Session of UN Commission on Human Rights Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd session of the United
Nations Commission on Human Rights ended here today. More than 100
resolutions and decisions concering the right of development,
racism and racial discrimination and violence against women and
children have been adopted since it began on March 10.
</P>
<P>
At the final meeting, delegates adopted a resolution on a world
congress on racism and racial discrimination. Only the United
States expressed its reservations over the resolution drafted by
Egypt on behalf of a group of African countries and developing
countries including China. It is decided that such a world
congress should be held in 1999 or at a time no later than 2001.
</P>
<P>
This year, with the support of developing countries, China
foiled for the seventh consecutive time an anti-China attempt by
US-led Western countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
