<HEADLINE> Six Inca Mausoleums Discovered in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- An archeological complex of six Inca
mausoleums has been discovered in north Peru, a cultural institute
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The National Institute of Culture (INC) said that the
mausoleums were discovered by the institute's technicians in a
place called "Laguna de los Condores" (Lagoon of the Condors),
9,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
It is the most important archeological discovery in past
decades in this part of the country, said the institute.
</P>
<P>
The site, which has architectonic characteristics of the
Chachapoyas Culture and is decorated with cave paintings, rendered
almost a hundred funerary bundles, fine weavings, ceramics, wood
carvings, crowns, and diverse objects of a great archeological
value.
</P>
<P>
Experts also determined that the zone of the discovery suffered
depredatory activity. To determine the exact magnitude of this
damage the technicians recorded the plundered areas in photographs
and videos.
</P>
<P>
The INC said it has coordinated with the provincial procurator
of Chachapoyas and national police an operation to rescue missing
pieces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
