<HEADLINE> Poland Calls for Equal Membership in NATO, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Polish President Alexander
Kwasniewski said here today that after the planned enlargement of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and European Union
(EU), the new members should enjoy equal status with the old ones.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Konrad Adenauer Foundation in Saint Augustin
near Bonn, Kwasniewski said Poland's membership in the EU and NATO
was not its final goal, but only "the beginning of a new European
policy of Poland".
</P>
<P>
Poland would step up its European activities after joining the
two major Western organizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski, who is on a two-day visit to Germany, met with
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
later on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kohl assured Kwasniewski that there would be "no membership of
less quality" after the NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the quick integration of Poland in the EU and the
NATO was an important goal of German foreign policy. Meanwhile he
also encouraged Poland to carry on its reforms consistently so as
to achieve the prerequisite of such an integration on its own.
</P>
<P>
During the talks between Kinkel and Kwasniewski, both sides
agreed that the processes of the EU and NATO enlargement should
not create new rifts or security grey zones in Europe. Especially
Russia should be equally incorporated into the new European-wide
security architecture, they stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
