<HEADLINE> Two More Records Highlight Second Day Short-course Swim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Two world records fell on the
second day of the World Short-Course Championships in Gothenburg
on Friday, with Australians smashing the men's 800 meters
freestyle relay and Claudia Poll of Costa Rica beating her own
world record in the 200m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
The Australian team of Michael Klim, Grant Hackett, William
Kirby and Matthew Dunn clocked 7:02.74, slicing more than two
seconds off the 11-year-old mark of 7:05.17.
</P>
<P>
Although Klim got a slow start and trailed Sweden's Anders
Lybring at the first 50m split, he surged back in the second 50
and the Australians never looked back. Sweden ended up with silver
and Britain was third.
</P>
<P>
Poll's 1:54.17 shattered the 1:55.42 record she set at the last
short-course championships two years ago in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Nian Yun of China took the silver behind Poll and Slovakia's
Martina Moravcova was third.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Voelker of Germany was denied a gold double after being
disqualified for staying underwater past the 15m mark in the 100m
backstroke. She had touched home first.
</P>
<P>
She opened Friday's finals with a 24.70 victory in the 50m
freestyle, beating America's Jennifer Thompson who touched home
first in the 100m freestyle the day before.
</P>
<P>
The duo of Thompson and Voelker ended Le Jingyi's freestyle
reign. Le, of China, who had won the 50m and 100m events at
previous two short-course championships, placed third in both.
</P>
<P>
China's Lu Donghua and Chen Yan took the gold and silver after
Voelker's disqualification and American Misty Hyman moved up to
third.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Patrik Isaksson, who had placed only seventh in the
preliminaries, won the men's 100m breaststroke before a boisterous
home crowd. She sped through the finals in 59.99.
</P>
<P>
Kristy Ellem of Australia won the women's 200m breaststroke in
2:22.68 and compatriot Natasha Bowron won the 800-meter freestyle
in 8:26.45. Cuba's Neisser Bent took the gold in the men's 200m
backstroke with 1:54.21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
