<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Ecoonomic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The export of Costa Rican industrial products
reached 332.2 million U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this
year, five percent more than that in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Textile products sales abroad were 112.85 million dollars, a
20.5 percent increase compared to the 93.65 million dollars earned
during the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan households income reached an average of
1,387 dollars a month during the period from December 1996 to
February 1997, practically the buying power registereed during the
same period a year before was 1,338 dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
Buying power in Montevideo registered a 1.5 percent increase,
while the urban areas of the interior of the country registered a
3.3 percent drop, according to data provided by the National
Statistics Institute.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Tourism Secretary Silvia Hernandez announced
that 28 entrepreneurial groups plan to invest 1.558 billion
dollars in the tourism sector between 1997 and 1998, a move that
will generate 50,000 jobs in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister foresees a 6 percent growth for the sector in
1997, with a total income of 7.3 billion dollars and 22.5 million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian poultry exports grew 31.9 percent in
volume and 22.1 percent in value during the first quarter of this
year, according to the Brazilian Association of Poultry
Exporters.
</P>
<P>
Association data show that domestic poultry sales increased
54.5 percent in volume and 49.2 percent in value during the first
three months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Petrobras, the biggest Brazilian state oil
enterprise, expects to produce 1.6 million barrels per day until
the year 2001 with a 14 billion dollar project of investments
between 1997 and 2000, said an official source.
</P>
<P>
Average daily output now is 876,000 barrels. The oil domestic
market grows 6 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
The company aims at supplying 75 percent of the domestic market
demand of oil and byproducts until the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaraguan micro and small enterprises have signed
contracts to export handicrafts to the United States and Europe
for half a million dollars approximately, announced Ricardo
Alvarado, president of the Program of Support to the Micro
Enterprise (Pamic).
</P>
<P>
The Pamic official said micro and small enterprises have a big
exporting potentiality, since it is estimated that this sector can
increase fivefold its income in five or ten years. Among the
articles this industry exports are ceramic articles, wood, metal,
and leather pieces, as well as hammocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
