<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Soars in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade rose sharply in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade volume from January to March hit 320 million
US dollars, representing a year-on-year growth of 54 percent. The
import volume rose 15.4 percent to 140 million US dollars, and the
export volume jumped 110 percent to 180 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, foreign trade in each month rose more
than 50 percent from the same month last year, according to the
regional department on foreign trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
While both imports and exports kept growing, exports
outstripped imports, leading to a trade surplus of more than 20
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The volume of general trade more than doubled that of the first
quarter of last year, showing a new round of growth for this type
of trade.
</P>
<P>
General trade accounted for more than 60 percent of exports in
all the three months; while border trade made up over half of
imports in each month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean mining industry exports reached 1,788.5
million U.S. dollars between January and the first half of March
this year, an 18 percent increase compared to the same period of
1996, said the Chilean Copper Commission
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, 1.503 billion dollars was earned from copper
exports, with a 24 percent increase over the same period of 1996.
The variation was attributed to an increase in the volume of the
remittances, because during that period the price of the metal in
the international markets was 109 cents of a dollar per pound,
while on the same period of 1996 it was 117 cents of a dollar per
pound.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Interamerican Development Bank (BID)
approved a 11.2 million dollar loan to increase the macroeconomic
and fiscal capacity of performance and to reinforce the financial
administration of the Panamanian government, according to
official sources. The credit has a 20-year maturity, with 4.5
years of grace, with a variable interest rate of 6.87 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Bankruptcy filings reduced 10 percent in the
the first quarter of this year, in comparison to the same period
of 1996, said the Central Bank of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
There were 190 cases of bankruptcy during that period, compared
to 212 in 1996, as a result of the higher economic activity. The
phenomenon resulted a recovery of the economic activity.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian hydrocarbons international trade
surged up in March of this year, with a 119 million dollar trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The volume of exports surpassed 7.5 million barrels, producing
income of 135.5 million dollars, while imports, mainly gasoline,
were 600,000 barrels, which cost 16.5 million dollars, according
to data provided by the oil state company. enditem


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
