<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nato Chief Urges Bosnian Parties to Do More for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Nato Secretary General Javier
Solana on Friday urged the leaders of Bosnia to make use of the
presence of Nato troops to achieve lasting peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Solana, together with ambassadors of Nato countries, met
members of the Bosnian presidency this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following the meeting, he said that the
Nato officials had made it clear to the the Bosnian presidency
that "the parties must take advantage of the security environment
(provided by Nato troops)...to begin to build their country and
build their society, and begin the long process of
reconciliation".
</P>
<P>
He said that he had demanded the Bosnian presidency, which
consists one representative each from the three ethnic nations, to
open other airhubs in the country for civilian travel, besides the
Sarajevo airport.
</P>
<P>
Solana refused to speculate what Nato will do after its current
peace-keeping mandate in Bosnia expires on June 30,1998, and said
that the military organization would rather concentrate on how to
implement the Dayton peace accords in the remaining 15 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
