<HEADLINE> Houston International Festival Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 18 (xinhua) -- The 26th Houston International
Festival which is honoring China with a spotlight on Chinese
culture opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Encompassing 20 blocks of downtown Houston, the festival
features six themed entertainment zones each celebrating the
heritage of various cultures from around the world.
</P>
<P>
New for this year's festival is the Asian Zone which features
the traditional and modern Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
Mayor of Houston Bob Lanier and Chinese Ambassador to the U.S.
Li Daoyu opened the festival by hitting "luo," a Chinese musical
instrument.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the opening ceremony were Sun Zhenyu, vice
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation and head of the
Chinese economic and trade delegation visiting Houston.
</P>
<P>
In celebration of its spotlight on Chinese culture, the
festival will introduce to American people the spectacular Beijing
Acrobatic Circus, traditional drummers from Shanxi province of
China and other performances.
</P>
<P>
The Southwestern Bell Chinese Village will be a unique museum
featuring the sights, sounds and aromas of both ancient and modern
Chinese culture to the visitors.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 artists from 25 countries around the world are
attending the festival and to display handmade arts and crafts on
several arts markets.
</P>
<P>
The Houston International Festival, starting from 1972, holds
annually in the Southwestern U.S. city, attracting about 1 million
visitors yearly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
