<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Security Advisors Urge Easing of Sanctions  on Iran, Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Two former U.S. national
security advisors today urged the Clinton administration to ease
economic sanctions against Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
upon the occasion of an article to be published in the journal
Foreign Affairs, Zbigniew Brzezinski and Brent Scowcroft told a
news briefing that the current U.S. policy toward the two
countries "lacks strategic viability and carries a high financial
and diplomatic cost."
</P>
<P>
They said the Clinton administration was hurting long-term U.S.
interests in securing energy from Central Asia by discouraging
pipeline routes through Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The United States should do nothing to preclude Central Asia's
eventual emergence, nor stand in the way of deals that might
facilitate it," their article said.
</P>
<P>
As regards to Iraq, the article said that if ongoing Iraqi oil
sales for food and medicine work, the United States should
consider allowing even more sales for humanitarian needs. If not,
the fraying international coalition against President Saddam
Hussein would collapse out of concern for innocent Iraqi people
who have been deprived under global economic sanctions over six
and a half years.
</P>
<P>
"America may have to consider modifying certain aspects of
Iraq's economic containment to keep its military strait-jacket
securely fastened," the article said.
</P>
<P>
The two former national security advisors suggested that the
Clinton administration adjust its policy, in consultation with
regional leaders, to give Iran and Iraq incentives to change
instead of just punishing them.
</P>
<P>
They said, however, the United States must also be ready to
take military action when necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
