<DOCNO> XIE19970419.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Senate to Pass Chemical Weapons Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
strongly urged the Senate today to ratify the Chemical Weapons
Convention, saying that a failure would put the United States "in
the company of pariah nations."
</P>
<P>
The Senate agreed Thursday to schedule a vote on April 24 on
the convention, which is to take effect on April 29. It requires a
two-thirds majority for approval.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the agreement, Clinton told a press conference that
he is "encouraged by the great progress", but he warned that
"hurdles" still exist in gaining the approval of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that agreement has been reached in the Senate on
28 conditions that will be included in the treaty's resolution of
ratification, but he added that there are still "a handful of
issues on which we fundamentally disagree."
</P>
<P>
"A vote for any of these killer amendments will prevent our
participation in the treaty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the convention ask for amendments to the
verification provisions of the treaty and demand that the U.S. not
participate in the treaty until Russia, Iraq and Libya join it.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that his country should lead in implementing the
convention. "We must lead in bringing this bipartisan treaty to
life and enforcing its rules," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we fail to ratify, other countries could back out as well.
We won't be able to enforce the treaty's rules or use its tools,
and our companies will face trade sanctions aimed at countries that
refuse to join," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I urge every member of the Senate to support the convention
when it comes to a vote next week," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which bans development, production, stockpiling,
transferring and use of chemical weapons, was signed in January
1993. Ratified by more than 70 countries up to now, the treaty
will take effect on April 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
